# Frontend auth interceptor discipline

## Rule
Token injection happens in exactly one place per app:
- Angular → HTTP interceptor.
- RTK Query (admin-frontend, quote-ai-frontend) → `prepareHeaders`.
- `ky` client (quote-ai-frontend) → global `hooks.beforeRequest`.

Exclusions (login endpoint, public health check, third-party services) are explicit, listed, and code-reviewed.

## Why
Multiple injection sites produce token leaks (sending the Freightify token to third parties) and missing tokens (skipping auth on new endpoints by accident). freightify-web's `service-communication.md` and admin-frontend's `prepareHeaders` pattern both make this explicit.

## Constraints
- No per-call manual `Authorization: Bearer ...` headers.
- The exclusion list is a constant at the top of the interceptor, commented with the reason for each entry.
- Token refresh is a single flow: detect 401, run refresh, retry original request; no duplicate refresh flows.
- Quote-ai-frontend's dual HTTP clients (Go app + Skipper/EFP) each have their own interceptor tuned to the right issuer — they do not share a token.

## Examples

### Good (RTK prepareHeaders)
```ts
baseQuery: fetchBaseQuery({
  baseUrl: '/api',
  prepareHeaders: (headers, { endpoint }) => {
    if (EXCLUDED_ENDPOINTS.has(endpoint)) return headers;
    const t = store.getState().auth.token;
    if (t) headers.set('Authorization', `Bearer ${t}`);
    return headers;
  },
});
```

### Bad
```ts
fetch('/api/ports', { headers: { Authorization: `Bearer ${localStorage.getItem('t')}` } });
```

